Master context — save as PROJECT_CONTEXT.md in your repo root
PROJECT: Mini-market e-commerce platform (rebuild from legacy PHP system)

BUSINESS CONTEXT:
- Grocery/mini-market ordering app. Customers order online, staff manually verify
  physical stock before confirming (no live inventory feed exists).
- Product catalog, pricing, and branch/shop data come ONLY from Microsoft Dynamics
  NAV 2015 (SQL Server), accessed read-only via a 15-minute polling sync job.
  We do NOT have a NAV developer license — no write-back to NAV is possible or
  permitted, ever, under any circumstance.
- Because stock data is only 15 minutes fresh at best, it can NEVER be used to
  auto-approve an order. It is a hint shown to staff, not a source of truth.
  Final availability confirmation is always a manual human action by a staff
  member physically checking the shelf.
- KEY FEATURE: if a customer orders multiple items and only some are in stock,
  the system must notify the customer of exactly which items are available and
  which aren't, and let them choose to proceed with the available subset or
  cancel entirely — never auto-cancel the whole order over one missing item.

NON-NEGOTIABLE RULES (do not violate these under any circumstances):
1. No endpoint, anywhere, in any role, may create/update/delete catalog items,
   prices, or branches. That data is synced from NAV read-only. If this
   constraint seems inconvenient for a task, stop and ask instead of adding
   a workaround endpoint.
2. All SQL must be parameterized via the ORM. Never string-concatenate a query.
3. Order and order-item status may only be changed by OrderStateMachineService.
   No controller or other service sets .status directly.
4. Every status change (order or item level) must write to an audit history
   table: who changed it, from what value, to what value, when.
5. Passwords: this app uses Google OAuth2 as the only login method. Do not
   build a password login flow unless explicitly asked.
6. Staff/admin accounts are allowlist-gated: a Google email must exist in a
   staff_allowlist table BEFORE any staff account or session is created.
   Customer accounts are open self-registration via Google OAuth2 — no allowlist.
7. Every state-changing endpoint needs input validation via DTOs (class-validator),
   auth guard, and role guard where applicable. No exceptions for "internal" or
   "admin-only" routes — those still need the guards, just with different roles.

TECH STACK:
- Backend: NestJS (TypeScript), PostgreSQL, TypeORM, Socket.IO (WebSocket gateways)
- Admin frontend: React + Vite + Tailwind CSS + TanStack Query
- Customer mobile app: Flutter
- Auth: Google OAuth2 + JWT access tokens (15 min) + rotating refresh tokens
- NAV connection: mssql package, read-only SQL login, scheduled via @nestjs/schedule

ORDER ITEM STATUS ENUM:
PENDING_REVIEW, AVAILABLE, PARTIALLY_AVAILABLE, UNAVAILABLE, CUSTOMER_DECLINED, CONFIRMED

ORDER STATUS ENUM:
PENDING_REVIEW, UNDER_REVIEW, AWAITING_CUSTOMER_DECISION, CONFIRMED, PREPARING,
READY, PICKED, DELIVERED, CANCELLED, EXPIRED

CODING STANDARDS:
- Write tests for services with business logic (state machine, sync, auth guards)
  at minimum. Controllers can be lighter.
- Small, reviewable commits. One logical change per commit.
- If a requirement is ambiguous, ask a clarifying question rather than guessing
  and moving on.
- Do not introduce new npm packages without saying which one and why.

