Phase 2 — NAV sync + read-only catalog
Read PROJECT_CONTEXT.md. Rule 1 (no catalog write endpoints) applies strictly
to everything in this phase.

Build the nav-sync and catalog modules.

1. nav-sync module:
   - Connect to SQL Server via the `mssql` package using a read-only
     connection string from env vars
   - Pull from these NAV views: view_item, view_sales_price,
     view_price_discount, view_brand, view_product_group, view_item_catagory
     (I'll give you the actual column names/sample rows before you write
     the query mapping — don't guess column names)
   - Upsert into Postgres catalog tables (items, brands, product_groups,
     categories, item_prices) — see schema below
   - Also sync current stock quantities per branch into item_stock_snapshot
     (nav_item_no, branch_id, qty, synced_at) — this is a HINT table only,
     label it clearly as such in code comments
   - Run on a schedule via @nestjs/schedule, every 15 minutes
   - Every run writes a row to nav_sync_log: started_at, finished_at,
     rows_synced, status (success/failed), error_message if failed
   - If a sync run fails, log it clearly and do NOT wipe existing cached
     data — keep serving the last good sync until the next successful one

2. catalog module — READ ONLY, no exceptions:
   - GET /catalog/categories, /catalog/categories/:id/groups,
     /catalog/items, /catalog/items/:id, /catalog/search?q=
   - Search should use Postgres pg_trgm trigram index on item title, not
     a LIKE '%x%' scan — set up the extension and index in a migration
   - Every response should include a note of when that item's data was
     last synced (synced_at), so the frontend can show staleness

3. Schema (create as TypeORM entities + migration):
   items(nav_item_no PK, title_en, title_am, brand_id, group_id, uom,
     image_url, synced_at)
   item_prices(nav_item_no, branch_id, price, discount_pct, valid_from,
     valid_to, synced_at)
   item_stock_snapshot(nav_item_no, branch_id, qty, synced_at,
     PRIMARY KEY(nav_item_no, branch_id))
