Phase 4 — Order state machine + shortage decision flow (headline feature)
Read PROJECT_CONTEXT.md. This is the most important phase — take your time
and confirm the state model with me before writing code if anything is unclear.

Build OrderStateMachineService — the ONLY place order/order_item status can
change (rule 3 in PROJECT_CONTEXT.md).

1. Staff review endpoints (role-gated, staff/admin only):
   - GET /admin/orders/queue — orders with status PENDING_REVIEW or
     UNDER_REVIEW, sorted oldest first
   - PATCH /admin/orders/:orderId/items/:itemId/review — body:
     { qtyAvailable: number, decision: 'AVAILABLE' | 'PARTIALLY_AVAILABLE' | 'UNAVAILABLE' }
     - validates decision matches qtyAvailable vs qtyRequested
     - sets line_status, reviewed_at, writes to order_status_history
     - sets order.status to UNDER_REVIEW if this is the first item reviewed
     - when this was the LAST unreviewed item on the order, trigger the
       completion check below in the same transaction

2. Completion check (runs after every item review, when no PENDING_REVIEW
   items remain on the order):
   - all items AVAILABLE → order.status = CONFIRMED, notify customer
     "order confirmed", write history row
   - all items UNAVAILABLE → order.status = CANCELLED, notify customer
     with reason, write history row
   - mixed result → order.status = AWAITING_CUSTOMER_DECISION,
     order.decision_deadline = now + 6 hours (configurable via env),
     notify customer with the available/unavailable breakdown and totals
     for both scenarios, write history row

3. Customer decision endpoint:
   - POST /orders/:id/decision — body: { decision: 'PROCEED' | 'CANCEL' }
   - only valid when order.status = AWAITING_CUSTOMER_DECISION and
     customer owns the order
   - PROCEED: unavailable/partially-declined items → CUSTOMER_DECLINED,
     available items → CONFIRMED, recalculate order.total from confirmed
     items only, order.status = CONFIRMED
   - CANCEL: order.status = CANCELLED
   - write history row either way

4. Expiry job:
   - @Cron job, runs every 5 minutes, finds orders where
     status = AWAITING_CUSTOMER_DECISION AND decision_deadline < now()
     (use the partial index from Phase 3), sets status = EXPIRED,
     notifies customer, writes history row

5. Continue lifecycle for CONFIRMED orders (mirrors the legacy system's
   flow but through the state machine service):
   PREPARING → READY → PICKED (pickup) / delivered via driver → DELIVERED
   - PATCH /admin/orders/:id/status endpoint for staff to advance through
     these, role-gated, validates only legal transitions are allowed
     (e.g. can't go from PREPARING straight to DELIVERED)

Write thorough unit tests for OrderStateMachineService covering: all-available
path, all-unavailable path, mixed path, customer proceed, customer cancel,
expiry, and rejection of illegal transitions. This service is the core of
the whole app — do not skip test coverage here even if you're tight on time
elsewhere.

Phase 5 — Notifications + WebSocket
Read PROJECT_CONTEXT.md.

Build the notifications module and WebSocket gateways described below,
and wire them into every notify-the-customer/notify-staff point created
in Phase 4 (replace any placeholder logging with real calls).

1. notifications table: id, customer_id (nullable, null = staff-targeted),
   staff_id (nullable), type, title, body, data (jsonb, e.g. order id),
   read_at (nullable), created_at

2. Two WebSocket namespaces:
   - /ws/customer — JWT required in handshake auth, joins room
     `customer:{userId}`. Events: order.statusChanged, order.decisionRequired
   - /ws/staff — JWT + role required in handshake, joins room
     `staff:orders-queue`. Events: order.newForReview, order.reviewedByOther
     (so two staff don't work the same order simultaneously)

3. NotificationsService.notify(...) should:
   - always write a row to the notifications table first (source of truth)
   - then push over WebSocket to the relevant room if connected
   - the DB write must never be skipped even if the WebSocket push fails

